  "local_port": 53148,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Guidance for writing Texas driver license exams?",
  "response": "Writing the Texas driver's license exam involves understanding the rules of the road, traffic signs, and safe driving practices. Here are some tips and guidance to help you prepare:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Study the Texas Driver Handbook**\n- The official **Texas Driver Handbook** is the primary resource for the exam. It covers:\n  - Traffic laws\n  - Road signs and signals\n  - Safe driving practices\n  - License requirements\n  - Special driving situations (e.g., school zones, construction zones)\n- Download the handbook from the **Texas Department of Public Safety (DPS)** website or pick up a copy at your local DPS office.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Understand the Exam Format**\n- The Texas driver's license exam consists of two parts:\n  1. **Written Knowledge Test** (30 multiple-choice questions)\n  2. **Road Signs Test** (10 questions)\n- You must answer **21 out of 30** questions correctly on the written test and **7 out of 10** on the road signs test to pass.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Focus on Key Topics**\n- **Traffic Laws**: Speed limits, right-of-way rules, seat belt laws, and DUI/DWI penalties.\n- **Road Signs and Signals**: Learn the shapes, colors, and meanings of all traffic signs and signals.\n- **Safe Driving Practices**: Defensive driving, sharing the road, and handling emergencies.\n- **Special Situations**: Driving in bad weather, school zones, and construction areas.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Take Practice Tests**\n- Practice tests are an excellent way to familiarize yourself with the exam format and test your knowledge.\n- Many websites and apps offer free Texas driver's license practice tests based on the official handbook.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Memorize Important Numbers**\n- Know key numbers like:\n  - Speed limits in residential areas, highways, and school zones.\n  - Blood alcohol concentration (BAC) limits (0.08% for adults, 0.00% for minors).\n  - Following distance (at least 2 seconds under normal conditions).\n\n---\n\n### **6. Review Road Signs**\n- Study the meaning of all road signs, including:\n  - Regulatory signs (e.g., stop, yield, speed limit)\n  - Warning signs (e.g., curves, pedestrian crossings)\n  - Guide signs (e.g., highway exits, route markers)\n\n---\n\n### **7. Prepare for the Day of the Exam**\n- Bring the required documents, such as:\n  - Proof of identity (e.g., passport, birth certificate)\n  - Proof of Social Security number\n  - Proof of Texas residency\n  - Completion certificate for a driver education course (if applicable)\n- Arrive early and stay calm during the test.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Retake the Exam if Necessary**\n- If you don\u2019t pass the first time, you can retake the exam after a waiting period. Use the time to review areas where you struggled.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Consider a Driver Education Course**\n- Taking a state-approved driver education course can help you better understand the material and may also reduce your insurance rates.\n\n---\n\nBy thoroughly studying the handbook, practicing with sample questions, and understanding Texas-specific driving rules, you\u2019ll be well-prepared to pass the Texas driver's license exam. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
